    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1199009127" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1199009127" />
    <a title="Mariel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/647547-mariel"><img alt="Mariel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1451321467p2/647547.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1199009127?book_show_action=true">Feb 12, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mariel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mariel" href="/user/show/647547-mariel">Mariel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">snow storms</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Mariel by: </span>
      you look nothing like David Bowie
  </div>


    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1199009127" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1465387417236963131"><blockquote>Ancient Japanese protocol stipulated that the Empreror be addressed with &quot;fear and trembling&quot;. I&apos;ve always loved the expression, which so perfectly describes the way actors in Samurai films speak to their leader, their voices tremulous with almost superhuman reverence.</blockquote><br/><br/>I would have fired Amélie. There&apos;s a judge and gavel going &quot;Next!&quot; That she should absolutely have been fired made me not care too much about her story. Work place nonsense beating the day dreams out of you with Alice in Wonderland</span>
  <span id="freeText1465387417236963131" style="display:none"><blockquote>Ancient Japanese protocol stipulated that the Empreror be addressed with "fear and trembling". I've always loved the expression, which so perfectly describes the way actors in Samurai films speak to their leader, their voices tremulous with almost superhuman reverence.</blockquote><br /><br />I would have fired Amélie. There's a judge and gavel going "Next!" That she should absolutely have been fired made me not care too much about her story. Work place nonsense beating the day dreams out of you with Alice in Wonderland bull shit. Maddening in the day, maddening at night. Office politics are bullshit. It's just as stupid in the Western world as in the East. The East-West comparisons didn't do as much for me as the zombie nod. It felt like working reading this it's sometimes so in depth on the ins and outs of paper pushing. Sitting and typing dead under those artificial lights day after day, hour after hour. But I would have fired Amélie (I can't believe they didn't when coming in the morning to her asleep on the floor with the garbage contents she dumped on herself for a blanket. Someone else has to clean it up, of course). I felt bad for the poor sap who had to fix all of her mistakes. She had no business doing accounting in the first place. I didn't feel all that sorry for HER in her Japanese import-export company job. Someone else had to do all of the work while she wasted twelve hours twisting her hands. I bet they had to stay late and still manage their own already heavy work load. I can picture them picturing their warm beds with longing. She doesn't quit because she doesn't want to "lose face". They don't like you anyway, Amélie! I don't know why they hired her if they weren't going to use her, except to have somebody at the bottom. There weren't any translating gigs? She knew French, Japanese, English and Chinese (maybe more). It was in the 1990s and they didn't like women much either. It would have been a shitty job for anyone who wants more than the Terrible Trivium from The Phantom Tollbooth life. No-face, with his eyedropper transferring a grain of sand from one pile to another pile. Make more money from one pile, into another one. Amélie envisions a corporate beast who is appeased like a God when they make more money. Maybe if she had stayed another year they could have sacrificed her to it. Amélie is almost oozing into a real spirit when she is losing her body in the windows. But her creepy obsession with her director supervisor Fubuki Mori ruins this story about incomprehensibility about Japanese corporate life. Fear and Trembling is a <i>memoir</i> in the worst sense of the word. She stares at her, envisions her hair tumbled in sexy afterglow. The nosing into her private life pissed me off. The Fubuki she wants as a glass, Amélie plunging into Amélie glass. It was so hollow. What business is it of yours if she's over twenty-five and not married, Amélie? The final page gets in a last word gloat that she's thirty and unmarried. For fuck's sake! I only hated her more when she spied on Fubuki's private tears in the rest room (because Amélie isn't the only woman who has to suck up shit every day). No, that is NOT a thing Westerners do (or it might be. Female coworkers have bitched about how awful I am because I wouldn't hold a stall to stall conversation). I would have hated her for it, anyway. Her Japanophile madness is too far. She didn't know what to do with her Japan of old, unknown Japan. I don't know how much of it was a hate-crush on Fubuki. Fubuki is the beautiful Japanese woman she wants to possess. I don't think she wanted to be her. It was worse than that. I see Amélie stomping through beautiful fields like radioactive I-love-you-not children giants. She'd love her if she had her where she wanted her, below Amélie. When she's a famous author and not the useless underling in the Yumimoto Corporation. I'm not buying any of it though. Maybe she did write her a "congratulations" note and maybe she didn't. It feels like book bullshit to sound good, though. Oh, she finally accepted me. Yeah, but you were a workplace leech, Amélie. People don't have to be your best friend and give you everything just because they work with you. She didn't owe you her life. There's a curious aspect to this when she's going off about cultural expectations of the Japanese woman that feels like the window she wants to throw herself into. Life for yourself ends at three, no dreams. So do you want to be three forever or does she think someone above them (probably another corporate window) has the answers? I don't think it's only in the East that looking like you have the right way is the only way. Mrs. Dalloway depressed me to piercing empty with this. Is it really better to always be quiet than thought a fool? Nothomb of this book does believe that in some sense because she stalks those like a rejected suitor. That's what she really reminded me of. An angry lover who talks too much about the dumper. All the while you're listening you know they'd drop everything if they actually called them (they won't). It grossed me out when she goes on about the president of the company as if he is God. She really believed this shit. <br /><br />Nothomb has no way of knowing if everyone is like that. I liked best her observations on names. A man names his son that means "to work". Whimsical names for the beaten into stiffness females. I know some of it has to be true because of that stiffness, just that she has no way of knowing that they agree in their organs with minds of their own.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1465387417236963131" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


