    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_587719553" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/587719553" />
    <a title="Aubrey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4119460-aubrey"><img alt="Aubrey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1472535045p2/4119460.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/587719553?book_show_action=true">Sep 04, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aubrey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aubrey" href="/user/show/4119460-aubrey">Aubrey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780312347321" href="/book/show/71453.Fear_and_Trembling">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=translated">translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=1-star">1-star</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=french">french</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=reality-check">reality-check</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=antidote-think-twice-all">antidote-think-twice-all</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=antidote-translated">antidote-translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=r-2019">r-2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=shorty-short">shorty-short</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=antidote-think-twice-read">antidote-think-twice-read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer587719553" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2078259508672023379">It says a lot about the 1001 Books Before You Die list when one of the few examples of Women in Translation (WIT) lit is the living incarnation of the disillusionment of a weaboo upon arriving in the Japan of their dreams. Considering the fact that the author maintains a fiction of a Japanese birth place to the point of it being inscribed on the back cover of my copy, this has to be one of the worst instances of contemporary Orientalism that I&apos;ve come across in some time, and I say this as someo</span>
  <span id="freeText2078259508672023379" style="display:none">It says a lot about the 1001 Books Before You Die list when one of the few examples of Women in Translation (WIT) lit is the living incarnation of the disillusionment of a weaboo upon arriving in the Japan of their dreams. Considering the fact that the author maintains a fiction of a Japanese birth place to the point of it being inscribed on the back cover of my copy, this has to be one of the worst instances of contemporary Orientalism that I've come across in some time, and I say this as someone who used to consume massive amounts of 'anime' and 'manga' in their youth. I picked this up due to a fortunate merging of last month's focus on WIT and this months' on 1001 BBYD, and I put it down wondering how this book sustains its repute. Then again, 'Memoirs of a Geisha' still gets raised on high despite a successful lawsuit for libel on part of the book's inspiration, so I suppose certain sects of non-Japanese people placed in rather powerful positions in pop culture are just frantically eager to inflict their fetishes on a people as a whole. Not the most encouraging thought, to the point that I have to wonder whether Nothomb coming from a family that's filthy rich had an impact on this erection of a rampantly embarrassing Euro-cultural touchstone.<br /><br />Beginning this text was rather familiar in a nauseating sort of way, as the complacent disconnect between the main character and her environment is cultivated amongst certain circles of Nipponophile fanatics. These days, feeling such on my own part with regards to any culture is a sign that I need to seek out more credible engagement than what I had been heretofore getting, but in this work, brief as it was, the cellophane between characters, customs, and countries is never broken, and what material I am sure was meant as satire comes across as nothing more than self-absorbed nonsense, and not even the type that resulted in some kernel that invokes compassion in myriad others. All in all, the most interesting thing about this book is the main character's queer desire (racist as it is) for her immediate supervisor, and it is the more overt appearance of this queer sensibility in Nothomb's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/834450.Le_Sabotage_amoureux" title="Le Sabotage amoureux by Amélie Nothomb" rel="nofollow noopener">Loving Sabotage</a> that inspired me to add that one as well. I'm no longer sure whether that theme will be sufficient to gt me through should that text be similarly in shambles, and while I'm keen on the promotion of WIT, I'm no babysitter of a reader, and if something manages to find its way onto various lists of repute (even the more crusty ones), I expect a magnificent ratio of bang to buck, not my own white teenage solipsism thrown back at me in a pretense of literature. Cause, honestly, how does anyone take something written in the vein of "She walked toward me with Hiroshima in her right eye and Nagasaki in her left," seriously? One may mewl and puke about translation, but French and English have much too much in common for someone to have subconsciously messed up that badly.<br /><br />Another day, another work of high repute revealed to not be all that. It's just a shame how this is a perfect example of what certain authors have to do to become famous and/or well regarded, or, rather, what certain authors <i>don't</i> have to do to achieve the same. In terms of returning to Nothomb, I'm truly hoping that a queer coming of age encourages less formulaic absurdity on the author's part, but as Leduc's 'La Bâtarde' demonstrates, it's stil possible to massively screw up in that kind of otherwise immensely welcome material. Anyway, this is off my shelf. On to pastures less choked in obtuse cliché.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2078259508672023379" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


